<section class="card">
  <h2>About Beans</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Direct-sow warm-season crop—wait for soil warmth, not just the calendar.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Beans are highly frost-sensitive and dislike cold soil.</strong>
    In short growing seasons, success depends less on starting early and more on waiting for warm conditions. Planting too soon into cool soil often results in slow germination, rot, or stalled growth.
  </p>

  <p>
    Beans grow quickly once temperatures are consistently warm, making them well-suited to northern U.S. and comparable Canadian climates—provided you time planting around soil warmth rather than last frost alone.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Cold Sensitivity & Temperature Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 70–85°F (21–29°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below 60°F (16°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Germination minimum:</strong> About 55°F (13°C) soil temperature</li>
    <li><strong>Stress threshold:</strong> Below 50°F (10°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Freeze damage:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Beans do not tolerate frost at any stage. A light freeze at 32°F (0°C) can kill seedlings and mature plants alike.
    Cool nights can also slow growth dramatically, extending time-to-harvest and increasing the risk of frost ending the crop before maturity.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planting Window Logic (Short Season)</h2>

  <p>
    Beans are one of the clearest examples of a crop where <strong>soil temperature matters more than calendar timing.</strong>
    The goal is to plant after last frost only once soil has warmed enough for fast germination and strong early growth.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Too early:</strong> slow germination, seed rot, uneven stands</li>
    <li><strong>On time:</strong> fast emergence, vigorous growth, earlier harvest</li>
    <li><strong>Too late:</strong> reduced buffer before fall frost</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Fall Frost Cutoff Modeling</h2>

  <p>
    Because beans are killed at 32°F (0°C), the first fall frost is a hard seasonal stop.
    Your planting date must allow enough time for flowering and pod fill before that boundary.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, the most reliable approach is to:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Choose varieties with shorter maturity (50–55 days when possible)</li>
    <li>Plant promptly once soil is warm</li>
    <li>Avoid stalling early growth with cold soil or wind exposure</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">Plan Backward From First Frost</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~900–1,200 GDD (base 50) for most bush beans</p>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days (GDD) estimate how much seasonal heat accumulates between your last and first frost in a typical year.
    Beans mature on a heat schedule: cooler summers slow development, while warmer summers compress days-to-maturity.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most bush beans need roughly <strong>50–70 frost-free days</strong> to reach harvest.
    Pole beans typically need a longer runway.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your 50% frost-free window is tight, beans can still work—if you choose shorter-maturity varieties and your seasonal heat budget is strong.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good under 100 days?</strong> Yes (bush beans are a common short-season win)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Often, unless you choose early varieties and your summer heat is reliable</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Sometimes helpful early (row cover for warmth), but beans are usually direct-sown</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Beans have <strong>no frost tolerance buffer</strong>. A freeze at 32°F (0°C) can end the crop immediately.
    That makes first frost the hard cutoff for maturity—and the reason risk margin matters.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Choose early bush varieties (often 50–55 days)</li>
    <li>Wait for warm soil, then plant on time (cold soil delays everything)</li>
    <li>Prioritize full sun and wind shelter to protect heat accumulation</li>
    <li>Use light row cover early only to add warmth (not to push into frost)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, beans are viable when your frost-free window provides enough time and your seasonal heat budget provides enough GDD.
    If the model barely works on paper, treat it as a low-buffer plan and choose earlier varieties.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>FAQ</h2>

  <h3>Can beans survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Beans are frost-sensitive and can be damaged or killed at 32°F (0°C).
  </p>

  <h3>Why didn’t my beans germinate?</h3>
  <p>
    Soil that is too cold (below about 55°F / 13°C) often leads to poor germination or seed rot.
  </p>

  <h3>Is it better to plant beans early or wait?</h3>
  <p>
    In short seasons, waiting for warm soil usually produces faster growth and earlier harvest than planting into cold conditions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Beans are killed at 32°F (0°C), so first frost is a hard seasonal stop.</li>
    <li>Most bush beans fit a 50–70 day runway, but slow starts in cold soil reduce buffer.</li>
    <li>Heat accumulation matters: if seasonal GDD is marginal, maturity becomes high-risk.</li>
    <li>Short-season success comes from warm-soil planting + early varieties + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    Model viability using: frost window (time) + seasonal heat budget (GDD) + variety maturity requirement (days/GDD) + buffer.
  </p>
</section>